21
00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:20.229
conduition: So, hi everyone. I'm conduition. I am a freelance, independent cryptographic engineer and security researcher.

22
00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:25.270
conduition: And recently my work has been focusing a lot on post-quantum signatures, and

23
00:07:25.390 --> 00:07:28.699
conduition: In that effort, I came up with this idea called hypertree pruning.

24
00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:46.470
conduition: This is an optimization to the SPHINCS+ signature algorithm, so before we get too deep into the weeds here, we should probably talk about SPHINCS+ first. I'm gonna guess that a lot of you are already familiar with it, but just to make sure we're all on the same page, and anybody watching the YouTube video would be later, I'm just gonna go over it again.

25
00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:56.360
conduition: SPHINCS+ is a hash-based stateless signature algorithm that's been standardized by NIST. It uses very conservative cryptographic assumptions, which we hope are post-quantum secure.

26
00:07:56.650 --> 00:08:11.139
conduition: It's built out of a hypertree structure, and this is kind of a tree of trees, a tree of Merkle trees that are arranged into different layers, where each layer of the tree signs the layer below using a Winternitz one-time signature key pair.

27
00:08:12.300 --> 00:08:27.110
conduition: The bottom level, at the very bottom of the Hypertree, is used to certify a set of FORS key pairs, where each 4 as key pair can be used to sign an actual message, like, say, a transaction, something that we care about for the purposes of the cryptosystem.

28
00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:37.500
conduition: The verifier will follow the signatures and a set of Merkle authentication pads all the way back up the hypertree to the very root of the root tree.

29
00:08:37.710 --> 00:08:44.540
conduition: And this root hash of the root tree is our public key. So for key generation, all we need to do is generate just the root tree.

30
00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:49.160
conduition: And for signing, we only need to generate the trees that are used for the signatures.

31
00:08:49.970 --> 00:09:05.229
conduition: And depending on the size of the overall hypertree, we have a given signature budget. And if we exceed this budget, if we create more than this many signatures, then the security of the key pair will start to degrade below a certain threshold, say, 128 bits.

32
00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:17.239
conduition: Now, for SLH-DSA, for example, that budget is typically quite large, 2 to the 64, but there are other parameter sets, and if you decrease the size of the parameter sets, you get lower budgets.

33
00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:19.209
conduition: Now, SPHINCS+ is great.

34
00:09:19.540 --> 00:09:27.829
conduition: But it's also very slow, especially for signing and key generation. The main reason why is because of the Winternitz one-time signature system.

35
00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:44.920
conduition: If you profile SPHINCS+, you'll see that over 90% of the runtime is dominated by Winternitz key generation, and most of those are for Winternitz keys that you never use, because you have to generate all of the leaves of this tree, even if you don't use them for certification signatures.

36
00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:50.230
conduition: Now, there are many ways known in the literature to optimize SPHINCS+.

37
00:09:50.450 --> 00:10:09.690
conduition: For example, there's algorithmic modifications, like SPHINCS+ plus C, or SPHINCS+ Alpha, and these give you mild speedups, as well as better signature sizes, but they're all incompatible with each other. If you have an SLH DSA verifier, they can't verify a SPHINCS+ plus C signature, for instance, and vice versa.

38
00:10:10.530 --> 00:10:29.260
conduition: But better are hardware techniques. These make better use of available hardware on whatever platform you're on, to run the same algorithms faster. You're squeezing better performance out of the same algorithms, and this can result in better speedups, orders of magnitude better, actually.

39
00:10:29.310 --> 00:10:40.620
conduition: Some of my recent work on Vulkan has shown you can actually improve on the reference implementation by more than an order of magnitude, and you get another order of magnitude speedup if you can use a GPU.

40
00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:52.230
conduition: And this is great, but it doesn't work on very weak or embedded systems. Say, hardware wallets, which is something, as cryptocurrency developers, we tend to care quite a bit about.

41
00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:54.599
conduition: So this leaves an unaddressed use case.

42
00:10:54.990 --> 00:11:09.449
conduition: Now, it's not looking good for the benchmarks of the current generation of hardware wallets. Ledger and Trezor both take on the order of minutes to produce an SLH DSA signature, and key generation is also not that great either.

43
00:11:10.070 --> 00:11:15.509
conduition: And the good news here is that of those two algorithms, key generation is the only one we urgently care about.

44
00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:26.630
conduition: Signing can be kicked down the road because, thankfully, we don't believe that there is a quantum computer available today to threaten us, and so we can continue using elliptic curves, for now.

45
00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:43.439
conduition: And hopefully the next generation of hardware wallets can be better optimized for signing. But key generation we do need. We want to be able to start migrating people over to post-quantum signature key pairs today, even if they continue to use elliptic curves as their primary daily spending.

46
00:11:43.470 --> 00:11:49.640
conduition: In Bitcoin specifically, we're hoping to have post-quantum fallback keys that use a,

47
00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:54.859
conduition: a second taproot leaf, with the new pay-to-Merkle root address format.

48
00:11:54.980 --> 00:12:06.170
conduition: And this way, people can start moving their money over, but still be using elliptic curves to spend today. And then, after Q-Day, they can switch over to a post-quantum scheme, if they haven't migrated to something else by then.

49
00:12:07.110 --> 00:12:19.579
conduition: So this is the idea from whence hypertree Pruning was born. Hypertree pruning is a way of trading off signature budget in exchange for faster performance, specifically of KeyGen, but also you can do the same for signing.

50
00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:24.590
conduition: In order to understand how it works, let's zoom in on XMSS.

51
00:12:24.810 --> 00:12:37.530
conduition: XMSS is a very key building block of SPHINCS+, and it essentially consists of a set of one-time signature key pairs, OTS keys, which you hash, and then join into a Merkle root structure.

52
00:12:37.650 --> 00:12:53.290
conduition: And the Merkle root of that tree is your public key. And to create a signature, you select an OTS key pair, you create a signature, and then you construct a Merkle proof that proves that that OTS key is part of your XMSS tree.

53
00:12:54.090 --> 00:12:59.270
conduition: Now, the downside of this construction is you can only issue a fixed number of signatures for a given key pair.

54
00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:09.940
conduition: Once all of your OTS keys are used, you can't make any more signatures, so you have a fixed budget, it's finite, and once you exceed it, you instantly break the security of the scheme.

55
00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:24.600
conduition: Now, the other downside to this is that if you want to increase your budget, you need to generate more OTS keys, and that can get very performance-intensive quickly, especially if you use Winternitz for your OTS system.

56
00:13:25.540 --> 00:13:36.399
conduition: And, one way to perhaps mitigate this, if you don't need so many signatures, but if the verifier expects you to have a tree of a certain height, is you could prune some of those OTS keys.

57
00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:48.870
conduition: This saves you the work of, oh, perhaps I should go back. What I mean by pruning here is you replace the hash of the OTS key with some pseudo-random garbage data.

58
00:13:49.070 --> 00:14:06.239
conduition: To the verifier, this looks the same as the hash of an OTS key. They can't tell the difference between the hash of a valid key and just some pseudo-random garbage. This saves you the work of generating the OTS key pair, and it does not change your signature format. And so the verifier's algorithm is unchanged.

59
00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:16.549
conduition: Now, this, of course, has a drawback. It means you have one less key pair for your signature budget, and maybe this is an acceptable trade-off.

60
00:14:16.920 --> 00:14:24.060
conduition: Perhaps the verifier expects you to have a tree that has a very large size, but you don't actually need to create that many signatures.

61
00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:29.469
conduition: Now, if you take this idea to its logical conclusion, you'll end up with maximal pruning.

62
00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:39.130
conduition: With a maximally pruned XMSS tree, you've removed every OTS key but one, and this is basically just a one-time signature scheme with extra steps.

63
00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:45.280
conduition: And if you can avoid doing this, you should, because it really doesn't add anything to the OTS scheme.

64
00:14:46.190 --> 00:14:50.829
conduition: But, this is very useful if you apply it to SPHINCS+.

65
00:14:51.620 --> 00:14:59.350
conduition: If you were to maximally prune the root tree of a SPHINCS+ hypertree, KeyGen becomes now very fast.

66
00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:03.100
conduition: Because now you'll only need to generate a single Winternitz key.

67
00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:06.509
conduition: And then a couple of surrogate hashes, which are very quick.

68
00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:20.350
conduition: Now, this does mean that you've decreased the size of the Hypertree overall, because now there are no Winternitz keys other than that one that you've left behind, that can be used to certify other levels of the Hypertree.

69
00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:27.320
conduition: This means when you're signing, you have to grind to find a randomizer that routes through that one unpruned Winternitz leaf.

70
00:15:27.980 --> 00:15:41.079
conduition: It also means that you now have many fewer FORS key pairs at the bottom level of the tree. And so, when you create signatures, each of those remaining FORS key pairs is far more likely to be used.

71
00:15:41.160 --> 00:15:48.870
conduition: And accordingly, you have to create fewer signatures overall to get the same level of security. So, your signature budget must drop.

72
00:15:49.720 --> 00:16:03.910
conduition: Now, the upside to all of this is that the verifier's behavior is still unchanged, as in XMSS. You don't need to worry about the verifier, because they can't tell the difference between the surrogate hashes and the actual OTS key hashes.

73
00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:09.920
conduition: Now let's look at an example to see what kind of performance gains we can get from this idea.

74
00:16:10.310 --> 00:16:17.199
conduition: So, with SLH-DSA128S parameter set, we have XMSS trees of height 9,

75
00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:22.760
conduition: That means there are 512 Winternitz keys per tree, including the root tree.

76
00:16:22.910 --> 00:16:31.299
conduition: So you can prune 511, at most, of those leaves from the root tree. This gives about 500 times faster key gen.

77
00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:35.219
conduition: And also a slight performance improvement on signing.

78
00:16:35.750 --> 00:16:41.849
conduition: The drawback is that your signature budget drops from 2 to the 64 down to 2 to the 55.

79
00:16:41.880 --> 00:17:00.280
conduition: It's a big drop. It's by a factor of 512. And the reason is because you only have one 512th as many FORS keys now. So the remaining ones are each 512 times more likely to be used, and therefore you can only produce one 512th as many signatures overall.

80
00:17:01.120 --> 00:17:04.329
conduition: So, what I've all just described there is

81
00:17:04.579 --> 00:17:11.070
conduition: Targeted mainly at improving key generation performance. But we can also use this technique to improve signing.

82
00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:23.199
conduition: Now, I'll skip the part where I explain why this is the case, but the… turns out the optimal way to improve signing performance with pruning is if you use what I call balanced pruning.

83
00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:28.830
conduition: This is where you prune each tree across each layer of the hypertree equally.

84
00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:38.860
conduition: By removing the same number of Winternitz keys from every tree across every layer, you get the optimal performance improvement relative to the cost of grinding.

85
00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:49.479
conduition: For example, if you were to, as I've shown in this diagram here, prune half of all the Winternitz keys in every tree, this would improve your signing performance by a factor of 2.

86
00:17:49.620 --> 00:17:52.310
conduition: In other words, it would have the signing runtime.

87
00:17:52.690 --> 00:18:03.960
conduition: Key generation performance would also be halved, because key generation is a subset of signing, and the root tree is the only thing you need to generate, and so there's only half as many Winternitz keys you need to generate.

88
00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:12.410
conduition: And again, just like with root tree pruning, the verifier's behavior is unchanged here. They don't notice that you're doing this at all.

89
00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:32.569
conduition: Now, there's a security footgun to what I've just described, which is, if you reuse a secret key with either different pruning techniques or with and without pruning, you can end up using the same Winternitz keys to sign different XMSS routes, which will result in forgeries.

90
00:18:32.700 --> 00:18:47.880
conduition: No good. So, to make sure you don't do that, you can either use dedicated key pairs for each pruning technique that you want to use, say, one key pair for balanced pruning, one key pair for maximal root tree pruning, and so on.

91
00:18:48.790 --> 00:18:59.869
conduition: Or you use domain separation, where you have different hash functions to generate different Winternitz keys for each of your different, pruning techniques.

92
00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:07.910
conduition: But, that's pretty much all for the technique. It's pretty minimal. So I'm gonna go over

93
00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:11.470
conduition: The high-level trade-offs

94
00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:24.390
conduition: HyperTree pruning is a… a new trade-off dimension, essentially. It gives you a way of sacrificing signature budget in exchange for better performance, and you can balance that performance between signing and key generation.

95
00:19:24.630 --> 00:19:30.690
conduition: You can go for really, really fast key generation, or you can go for a little bit faster signing.

96
00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:47.739
conduition: And the verification algorithms aren't affected by this trade-off at all. So this is great if you had, say, a single parameter set that's been enshrined in consensus, and now you have a really weedy hardware platform that has to satisfy that parameter set. Well, that hardware wallet could,

97
00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:54.089
conduition: Use pruning to get better performance. And for a hardware wallet, that's a worthwhile trade-off to make.

98
00:19:54.090 --> 00:20:09.090
conduition: Because every time the user signs a transaction, they have to manually interact with the device, so it's reasonable to expect that such a device wouldn't produce that many signatures. We certainly don't need 2 to the 64. Even 2 to the 55 is probably overkill.

99
00:20:10.100 --> 00:20:20.729
conduition: Now, this generalizes as well to any HyperTree-based cryptosystem, such as XMSS Multitree, and perhaps other HyperTree-based cryptosystems that might be invented in the future.

100
00:20:21.620 --> 00:20:30.590
conduition: Now, there are drawbacks, of course. As I've shown before, pruned and unpruned keys are incompatible, and it can be security footgun if you're not careful.

101
00:20:30.790 --> 00:20:44.310
conduition: Speaking of security footguns, I could very easily foresee developers misusing this if they prune too heavily, especially for software wallets, where you can essentially create an unbound number of signatures without user interaction.

102
00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:46.169
conduition: Depending on the context.

103
00:20:46.610 --> 00:20:55.130
conduition: So, if you sacrifice too much security, signature budget, you could end up with, users who lower their key pairs too much, or…

104
00:20:55.620 --> 00:20:58.830
conduition: Or other potential, unknown unknowns.

105
00:20:59.990 --> 00:21:16.699
conduition: Now, this also affects privacy, because although I've said that, to an honest verifier, pruning is indistinguishable, it is distinguishable to an observant verifier who knows about pruning, and wants to specifically identify and fingerprint wallets that use it.

106
00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:19.620
conduition: For example, with root tree pruning.

107
00:21:19.960 --> 00:21:28.279
conduition: If you observe many signatures from the same key pair, you'll notice they keep reusing the same, top-level tree leaf.

108
00:21:28.600 --> 00:21:31.839
conduition: And that can be identified over time, probabilistically.

109
00:21:32.940 --> 00:21:39.759
conduition: And of course, the other thing worth mentioning is that hypertree pruning isn't as efficient as just selecting a better parameter set.

110
00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:46.519
conduition: Like, maximal root tree pruning is essentially the same as just having a hypertree of one fewer layer.

111
00:21:47.300 --> 00:21:55.459
conduition: So, you really would be better off if you could just random, or if you could just arbitrarily select different parameter sets on the verifier.

112
00:21:55.650 --> 00:22:06.039
conduition: However, that said, if the verifier is static, then hypertree pruning is a great way of trading off, budget for performance, in order to please the verifier.

113
00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:19.920
conduition: Alright, and that's it, but there… I did skip a few things in this talk. I didn't talk about why balanced pruning is the best strategy to optimize signing performance. I didn't explain how grinding affects performance.

114
00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:23.569
conduition: And I didn't explain how different parameter sets work with this.

115
00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:30.800
conduition: So, in order to answer all these questions, you can see my article. It's posted right here, but I'd be glad to take any questions if we have any extra time.

