123
00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:31.440
conduition: That would be a staple scheme, essentially, and that is something that we're considering, especially in the Bitcoin world.

124
00:23:31.550 --> 00:23:47.669
conduition: You would need to maintain a counter of how many signatures you use, or you could optionally refer to the blockchain, which has been discussed before, but in many cases, that's not reliable as a source of truth, since you don't know for sure how many signatures have been published. You only know how many are on-chain.

125
00:23:47.840 --> 00:23:52.939
conduition: The other thing worth mentioning about those parameter sets is that they use a single layer.

126
00:23:53.070 --> 00:23:56.289
conduition: The main advantage of Hypertree pruning is

127
00:23:56.570 --> 00:24:04.830
conduition: That there are multiple layers, and so if you prune one layer, say, the root tree, which makes for faster key generation, then

128
00:24:04.870 --> 00:24:19.219
conduition: you only need to generate, like, maybe one or two or a few Winternitz keys at the root tree, but then the rest of your layers could still be intact, and you would still get the rapid growth of your hypertree from thence onwards. If you only have one layer.

129
00:24:19.250 --> 00:24:26.549
conduition: you only get to prune that one layer, so, you know, signing and keygen would be improved by the same factor,

130
00:24:26.970 --> 00:24:37.689
conduition: And it's… I'm not sure, I haven't done the math on it, but I imagine the performance savings might be less significant compared to what they would be for a hypertree of multiple layers.

131
