conduition: The benchmarking? No, I haven't implemented it. And that's mainly because I just didn't have the time.

149
00:26:31.440 --> 00:26:35.880
conduition: The, idea is mostly aimed at, hardware wallets, so…

150
00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:48.550
conduition: the first thing that I would probably want to do is implement it on a software wallet, and then start looking at talking to hardware wallet developers about this. I presented this idea to Ledger and Trezor. I haven't heard back from them on it yet.

151
00:26:48.830 --> 00:26:56.049
conduition: Now, as for benchmarking it, it's pretty easy to figure out what the relative performance gains would be.

152
00:26:56.220 --> 00:26:58.259
conduition: You would just first…

153
00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:07.300
conduition: Isolate the performance of the FORS, the few times signature scheme, and just leave that off to the side, because that scheme is unaffected by pruning.

154
00:27:07.450 --> 00:27:21.390
conduition: And then you would take the remaining runtime of the algorithm and, slice it up according to how many Winternitz keys that you prune. So, for example, with KeyGen, if you prune maximally of the root tree.

155
00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:36.970
conduition: you get, only 1 out of 512 keys. So, because Winternitz dominates the runtime in Hypertree, you can deduce that key generation will be about 512 times faster.

156
00:27:37.910 --> 00:27:56.030
conduition: And as for signing, because FORS is still a factor, you first take your HyperTree signing runtime, which is a subset of the signing procedure, and then you slice that up according to how many Winternitz keys you've pruned, so say if you pruned, half of all the keys in a HyperTree.

157
00:27:56.030 --> 00:28:02.680
conduition: Then you could assume the runtime will be about half, and then you add the 4 as signing time on top of that.

158
00:28:02.730 --> 00:28:14.120
conduition: It's pretty easy math, surprisingly, because there's… Winternitz is absolutely the dominating factor. It doesn't actually, other factors don't affect the signing performance nearly as much.

159
00:28:18.670 --> 00:28:19.400
Antonio Sanso: Alright.

160
00:28:20.220 --> 00:28:22.510
Antonio Sanso: There's a question for you, okay.

161
00:28:22.990 --> 00:28:38.249
Antonio Sanso: Will both EL and CL use the same PQS algorithm as SPHINCS+? Alan, I can already answer here, no. Because, for a consensus, we can actually keep the state. So consensus, we already know, is using XMSS.

162
00:28:38.970 --> 00:28:43.900
Antonio Sanso: So, in that case, we can release statful signatures. This is not the case for Yale.

163
00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:48.159
Antonio Sanso: I hope it answers your question.

164
00:28:49.260 --> 00:28:54.990
conduition: So one interesting question that affects whether hypertree pruning is worthwhile would be.

165
00:28:55.100 --> 00:29:03.230
conduition: whether your verifiers are flexible or not. If your verifiers are flexible and you can dictate parameter sets more flexibly.

166
00:29:03.230 --> 00:29:17.490
conduition: the temperature pruning just isn't that relevant to you. But if your verifiers are fixed, well, then it does become quite useful, because then, your verifiers might have a very large parameter set that they expect you to satisfy, and your signers might not be able to if they're on constrained platforms.

167
00:29:17.860 --> 00:29:27.190
conduition: I see someone's asking about side channel attacks here. I'm actually not that familiar with the masked version you're talking about.

168
00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:38.820
conduition: But, whatever, masking that you're applying to SPHINCS+ can equally be applied to, a pruned signer, just as well.

169
00:29:38.820 --> 00:29:48.379
conduition: And I imagine that whatever effect on performance masking might have, the same performance effects will apply to hypertree pruning at the same constant factor.

170
00:29:55.910 --> 00:29:56.590
Antonio Sanso: Right.

